7 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
8 // ----
9 // This implements a simple VLIW packetizer using DFA. The packetizer works on ----
10 // machine basic blocks. For each instruction I in BB, the packetizer consults ----
11 // the DFA to see if machine resources are available to execute I. If so, the ----
12 // packetizer checks if I depends on any instruction J in the current packet. ----
13 // If no dependency is found, I is added to current packet and machine resource ----
14 // is marked as taken. If any dependency is found, a target API call is made to ----
15 // prune the dependence. ----
16 // ----
17 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
18 ----

147 // Check if FirstI modifies a register that SecondI reads. ----
148 static bool hasWriteToReadDep(const MachineInstr &FirstI, 0
149 const MachineInstr &SecondI, ----
150 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) { ----
151 for (auto &MO : FirstI.operands()) { 0
152 if (!MO.isReg() || !MO.isDef()) 0
153 continue; 0
154 Register R = MO.getReg(); 0
155 if (SecondI.readsRegister(R, TRI)) 0

157 } ----

162 static MachineBasicBlock::iterator moveInstrOut(MachineInstr &MI, 0
163 MachineBasicBlock::iterator BundleIt, bool Before) { ----
164 MachineBasicBlock::instr_iterator InsertPt; 0
165 if (Before) 0
166 InsertPt = BundleIt.getInstrIterator(); 0
167 else ----
168 InsertPt = std::next(BundleIt).getInstrIterator(); 0
169 ----
170 MachineBasicBlock &B = *MI.getParent(); 0
171 // The instruction should at least be bundled with the preceding instruction ----
172 // (there will always be one, i.e. BUNDLE, if nothing else). ----
173 assert(MI.isBundledWithPred()); 0
174 if (MI.isBundledWithSucc()) { 0
175 MI.clearFlag(MachineInstr::BundledSucc); 0
176 MI.clearFlag(MachineInstr::BundledPred); 0
177 } else { ----
178 // If it's not bundled with the successor (i.e. it is the last one ----
179 // in the bundle), then we can simply unbundle it from the predecessor, ----
180 // which will take care of updating the predecessor's flag. ----
181 MI.unbundleFromPred(); 0
182 } ----
183 B.splice(InsertPt, &B, MI.getIterator()); 0
184 ----
185 // Get the size of the bundle without asserting. ----
186 MachineBasicBlock::const_instr_iterator I = BundleIt.getInstrIterator(); 0
187 MachineBasicBlock::const_instr_iterator E = B.instr_end(); 0
188 unsigned Size = 0; 0
189 for (++I; I != E && I->isBundledWithPred(); ++I) 0
190 ++Size; 0
191 ----
192 // If there are still two or more instructions, then there is nothing ----
193 // else to be done. ----
194 if (Size > 1) 0
195 return BundleIt; 0
196 ----
197 // Otherwise, extract the single instruction out and delete the bundle. ----
198 MachineBasicBlock::iterator NextIt = std::next(BundleIt); 0
199 MachineInstr &SingleI = *BundleIt->getNextNode(); 0
200 SingleI.unbundleFromPred(); 0
201 assert(!SingleI.isBundledWithSucc()); 0
202 BundleIt->eraseFromParent(); 0
203 return NextIt; 0
204 } ----

206 bool HexagonPacketizer::runOnMachineFunction(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
207 // FIXME: This pass causes verification failures. ----
208 MF.getProperties().set( 0
209 MachineFunctionProperties::Property::FailsVerification); ----
210 ----
211 auto &HST = MF.getSubtarget(); 0
212 HII = HST.getInstrInfo(); 0
213 HRI = HST.getRegisterInfo(); 0
214 auto &MLI = getAnalysis(); 0
215 auto *AA = &getAnalysis().getAAResults(); 0
216 auto *MBPI = &getAnalysis(); 0
217 ----
218 if (EnableGenAllInsnClass) 0
219 HII->genAllInsnTimingClasses(MF); 0
220 ----
221 // Instantiate the packetizer. ----
222 bool MinOnly = Minimal || DisablePacketizer || !HST.usePackets() || 0
223 skipFunction(MF.getFunction()); 0
224 HexagonPacketizerList Packetizer(MF, MLI, AA, MBPI, MinOnly); 0
225 ----
226 // DFA state table should not be empty. ----
227 assert(Packetizer.getResourceTracker() && "Empty DFA table!"); 0
228 ----
229 // Loop over all basic blocks and remove KILL pseudo-instructions ----
230 // These instructions confuse the dependence analysis. Consider: ----
231 // D0 = ... (Insn 0) ----
232 // R0 = KILL R0, D0 (Insn 1) ----
233 // R0 = ... (Insn 2) ----
234 // Here, Insn 1 will result in the dependence graph not emitting an output ----
235 // dependence between Insn 0 and Insn 2. This can lead to incorrect ----
236 // packetization ----
237 for (MachineBasicBlock &MB : MF) { 0
238 for (MachineInstr &MI : llvm::make_early_inc_range(MB)) 0
239 if (MI.isKill()) 0
240 MB.erase(&MI); 0
241 } ----
242 ----
243 // TinyCore with Duplexes: Translate to big-instructions. ----
244 if (HST.isTinyCoreWithDuplex()) 0
245 HII->translateInstrsForDup(MF, true); 0
246 ----
247 // Loop over all of the basic blocks. ----
248 for (auto &MB : MF) { 0
249 auto Begin = MB.begin(), End = MB.end(); 0
250 while (Begin != End) { 0
251 // Find the first non-boundary starting from the end of the last ----
252 // scheduling region. ----
253 MachineBasicBlock::iterator RB = Begin; 0
254 while (RB != End && HII->isSchedulingBoundary(*RB, &MB, MF)) 0
255 ++RB; 0
256 // Find the first boundary starting from the beginning of the new ----
257 // region. ----
258 MachineBasicBlock::iterator RE = RB; 0
259 while (RE != End && !HII->isSchedulingBoundary(*RE, &MB, MF)) 0
260 ++RE; 0
261 // Add the scheduling boundary if it's not block end. ----
262 if (RE != End) 0
263 ++RE; 0
264 // If RB == End, then RE == End. ----
265 if (RB != End) 0
266 Packetizer.PacketizeMIs(&MB, RB, RE); 0
267 ----
268 Begin = RE; 0
269 } ----
270 } ----
271 ----
272 // TinyCore with Duplexes: Translate to tiny-instructions. ----
273 if (HST.isTinyCoreWithDuplex()) 0
274 HII->translateInstrsForDup(MF, false); 0
275 ----
276 Packetizer.unpacketizeSoloInstrs(MF); 0
277 return true; 0
278 } 0

302 bool HexagonPacketizerList::isCallDependent(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
303 SDep::Kind DepType, unsigned DepReg) { ----
304 // Check for LR dependence. ----
305 if (DepReg == HRI->getRARegister()) 0
306 return true; 0
307 ----
308 if (HII->isDeallocRet(MI)) 0
309 if (DepReg == HRI->getFrameRegister() || DepReg == HRI->getStackRegister()) 0
310 return true; 0
311 ----
312 // Call-like instructions can be packetized with preceding instructions ----
313 // that define registers implicitly used or modified by the call. Explicit ----
314 // uses are still prohibited, as in the case of indirect calls: ----
315 // r0 = ... ----
316 // J2_jumpr r0 ----
317 if (DepType == SDep::Data) { 0
318 for (const MachineOperand &MO : MI.operands()) 0
319 if (MO.isReg() && MO.getReg() == DepReg && !MO.isImplicit()) 0
320 return true; 0
321 } ----
322 ----
323 return false; 0
324 } ----

359 bool HexagonPacketizerList::isNewifiable(const MachineInstr &MI, 0

361 // Vector stores can be predicated, and can be new-value stores, but ----
362 // they cannot be predicated on a .new predicate value. ----

364 if (HII->isHVXVec(MI) && MI.mayStore()) 0
365 return false; 0
366 return HII->isPredicated(MI) && HII->getDotNewPredOp(MI, nullptr) > 0; 0
367 } ----
368 // If the class is not PredRegs, it could only apply to new-value stores. ----
369 return HII->mayBeNewStore(MI); 0

384 void HexagonPacketizerList::cleanUpDotCur() { 0
385 MachineInstr *MI = nullptr; 0
386 for (auto *BI : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
387 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Cleanup packet has "; BI->dump();); 0
388 if (HII->isDotCurInst(*BI)) { 0
389 MI = BI; 0
390 continue; 0
391 } ----
392 if (MI) { 0
393 for (auto &MO : BI->operands()) 0
394 if (MO.isReg() && MO.getReg() == MI->getOperand(0).getReg()) 0
395 return; 0
396 } ----
397 } ----
398 if (!MI) 0
399 return; 0
400 // We did not find a use of the CUR, so de-cur it. ----
401 MI->setDesc(HII->get(HII->getNonDotCurOp(*MI))); 0
402 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Demoted CUR "; MI->dump();); 0
403 } ----

405 // Check to see if an instruction can be dot cur. ----
406 bool HexagonPacketizerList::canPromoteToDotCur(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
407 const SUnit *PacketSU, unsigned DepReg, MachineBasicBlock::iterator &MII, ----
408 const TargetRegisterClass *RC) { ----
409 if (!HII->isHVXVec(MI)) 0
410 return false; 0
411 if (!HII->isHVXVec(*MII)) 0
412 return false; 0
413 ----
414 // Already a dot new instruction. ----
415 if (HII->isDotCurInst(MI) && !HII->mayBeCurLoad(MI)) 0
416 return false; 0
417 ----
418 if (!HII->mayBeCurLoad(MI)) 0
419 return false; 0
420 ----
421 // The "cur value" cannot come from inline asm. ----
422 if (PacketSU->getInstr()->isInlineAsm()) 0
423 return false; 0
424 ----
425 // Make sure candidate instruction uses cur. ----
426 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Can we DOT Cur Vector MI\n"; MI.dump(); 0
427 dbgs() << "in packet\n";); ----
428 MachineInstr &MJ = *MII; 0
429 LLVM_DEBUG({ 0
430 dbgs() << "Checking CUR against "; ----
431 MJ.dump(); ----
432 }); ----
433 Register DestReg = MI.getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
434 bool FoundMatch = false; 0
435 for (auto &MO : MJ.operands()) 0
436 if (MO.isReg() && MO.getReg() == DestReg) 0
437 FoundMatch = true; 0
438 if (!FoundMatch) 0
439 return false; 0
440 ----
441 // Check for existing uses of a vector register within the packet which ----
442 // would be affected by converting a vector load into .cur formt. ----
443 for (auto *BI : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
444 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "packet has "; BI->dump();); 0
445 if (BI->readsRegister(DepReg, MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo())) 0
446 return false; 0
447 } ----
448 ----
449 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Can Dot CUR MI\n"; MI.dump();); 0
450 // We can convert the opcode into a .cur. ----
451 return true; 0
452 } ----

476 bool HexagonPacketizerList::useCallersSP(MachineInstr &MI) { 0

490 if (HII->isValidOffset(Opc, NewOff, HRI)) { 0
491 Off.setImm(NewOff); 0
492 return true; 0
493 } ----
494 return false; 0

513 /// Return true if we can update the offset in MI so that MI and MJ ----
514 /// can be packetized together. ----
515 bool HexagonPacketizerList::updateOffset(SUnit *SUI, SUnit *SUJ) { 0
516 assert(SUI->getInstr() && SUJ->getInstr()); 0
517 MachineInstr &MI = *SUI->getInstr(); 0
518 MachineInstr &MJ = *SUJ->getInstr(); 0
519 ----
520 unsigned BPI, OPI; ----
521 if (!HII->getBaseAndOffsetPosition(MI, BPI, OPI)) 0
522 return false; 0
523 unsigned BPJ, OPJ; ----
524 if (!HII->getBaseAndOffsetPosition(MJ, BPJ, OPJ)) 0
525 return false; 0
526 Register Reg = MI.getOperand(BPI).getReg(); 0
527 if (Reg != MJ.getOperand(BPJ).getReg()) 0
528 return false; 0
529 // Make sure that the dependences do not restrict adding MI to the packet. ----
530 // That is, ignore anti dependences, and make sure the only data dependence ----
531 // involves the specific register. ----
532 for (const auto &PI : SUI->Preds) 0
533 if (PI.getKind() != SDep::Anti && 0
534 (PI.getKind() != SDep::Data || PI.getReg() != Reg)) 0
535 return false; 0
536 int Incr; ----
537 if (!HII->getIncrementValue(MJ, Incr)) 0
538 return false; 0
539 ----
540 int64_t Offset = MI.getOperand(OPI).getImm(); 0
541 if (!HII->isValidOffset(MI.getOpcode(), Offset+Incr, HRI)) 0
542 return false; 0
543 ----
544 MI.getOperand(OPI).setImm(Offset + Incr); 0
545 ChangedOffset = Offset; 0
546 return true; 0
547 } ----

549 /// Undo the changed offset. This is needed if the instruction cannot be ----
550 /// added to the current packet due to a different instruction. ----
551 void HexagonPacketizerList::undoChangedOffset(MachineInstr &MI) { 0
552 unsigned BP, OP; ----
553 if (!HII->getBaseAndOffsetPosition(MI, BP, OP)) 0
554 llvm_unreachable("Unable to find base and offset operands."); 0
555 MI.getOperand(OP).setImm(ChangedOffset); 0
556 } 0

564 /// Returns true if an instruction is predicated on p0 and false if it's ----
565 /// predicated on !p0. ----
566 static PredicateKind getPredicateSense(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
567 const HexagonInstrInfo *HII) { ----
568 if (!HII->isPredicated(MI)) 0
569 return PK_Unknown; 0
570 if (HII->isPredicatedTrue(MI)) 0
571 return PK_True; 0
572 return PK_False; 0

574 ----
575 static const MachineOperand &getPostIncrementOperand(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
576 const HexagonInstrInfo *HII) { ----
577 assert(HII->isPostIncrement(MI) && "Not a post increment operation."); 0
578 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
579 // Post Increment means duplicates. Use dense map to find duplicates in the ----
580 // list. Caution: Densemap initializes with the minimum of 64 buckets, ----
581 // whereas there are at most 5 operands in the post increment. ----
582 DenseSet DefRegsSet; 0
583 for (auto &MO : MI.operands()) 0
584 if (MO.isReg() && MO.isDef()) 0
585 DefRegsSet.insert(MO.getReg()); 0
586 ----
587 for (auto &MO : MI.operands()) 0
588 if (MO.isReg() && MO.isUse() && DefRegsSet.count(MO.getReg())) 0
589 return MO; 0
590 #else ----
591 if (MI.mayLoad()) { ----
592 const MachineOperand &Op1 = MI.getOperand(1); ----
593 // The 2nd operand is always the post increment operand in load. ----
594 assert(Op1.isReg() && "Post increment operand has be to a register."); ----
595 return Op1; ----
596 } ----
597 if (MI.getDesc().mayStore()) { ----
598 const MachineOperand &Op0 = MI.getOperand(0); ----
599 // The 1st operand is always the post increment operand in store. ----
600 assert(Op0.isReg() && "Post increment operand has be to a register."); ----
601 return Op0; ----
602 } ----
603 #endif ----
604 // we should never come here. ----
605 llvm_unreachable("mayLoad or mayStore not set for Post Increment operation"); 0
606 } 0
607 ----
608 // Get the value being stored. ----
609 static const MachineOperand& getStoreValueOperand(const MachineInstr &MI) { 0
610 // value being stored is always the last operand. ----
611 return MI.getOperand(MI.getNumOperands()-1); 0
612 } ----
613 ----
614 static bool isLoadAbsSet(const MachineInstr &MI) { 0
615 unsigned Opc = MI.getOpcode(); 0
616 switch (Opc) { 0
617 case Hexagon::L4_loadrd_ap: 0
618 case Hexagon::L4_loadrb_ap: ----
619 case Hexagon::L4_loadrh_ap: ----
620 case Hexagon::L4_loadrub_ap: ----
621 case Hexagon::L4_loadruh_ap: ----
622 case Hexagon::L4_loadri_ap: ----
623 return true; 0
624 } ----
625 return false; 0
626 } ----
627 ----
628 static const MachineOperand &getAbsSetOperand(const MachineInstr &MI) { 0
629 assert(isLoadAbsSet(MI)); 0
630 return MI.getOperand(1); 0
631 } ----
632 ----
633 // Can be new value store? ----
634 // Following restrictions are to be respected in convert a store into ----
635 // a new value store. ----
636 // 1. If an instruction uses auto-increment, its address register cannot ----
637 // be a new-value register. Arch Spec 5.4.2.1 ----
638 // 2. If an instruction uses absolute-set addressing mode, its address ----
639 // register cannot be a new-value register. Arch Spec 5.4.2.1. ----
640 // 3. If an instruction produces a 64-bit result, its registers cannot be used ----
641 // as new-value registers. Arch Spec 5.4.2.2. ----
642 // 4. If the instruction that sets the new-value register is conditional, then ----
643 // the instruction that uses the new-value register must also be conditional, ----
644 // and both must always have their predicates evaluate identically. ----
645 // Arch Spec 5.4.2.3. ----
646 // 5. There is an implied restriction that a packet cannot have another store, ----
647 // if there is a new value store in the packet. Corollary: if there is ----
648 // already a store in a packet, there can not be a new value store. ----
649 // Arch Spec: 3.4.4.2 ----
650 bool HexagonPacketizerList::canPromoteToNewValueStore(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
651 const MachineInstr &PacketMI, unsigned DepReg) { ----
652 // Make sure we are looking at the store, that can be promoted. ----
653 if (!HII->mayBeNewStore(MI)) 0
654 return false; 0
655 ----
656 // Make sure there is dependency and can be new value'd. ----
657 const MachineOperand &Val = getStoreValueOperand(MI); 0
658 if (Val.isReg() && Val.getReg() != DepReg) 0
659 return false; 0
660 ----
661 const MCInstrDesc& MCID = PacketMI.getDesc(); 0
662 ----
663 // First operand is always the result. ----
664 const TargetRegisterClass *PacketRC = HII->getRegClass(MCID, 0, HRI, MF); 0
665 // Double regs can not feed into new value store: PRM section: 5.4.2.2. ----
666 if (PacketRC == &Hexagon::DoubleRegsRegClass) 0
667 return false; 0
668 ----
669 // New-value stores are of class NV (slot 0), dual stores require class ST ----
670 // in slot 0 (PRM 5.5). ----
671 for (auto *I : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
672 SUnit *PacketSU = MIToSUnit.find(I)->second; 0
673 if (PacketSU->getInstr()->mayStore()) 0
674 return false; 0
675 } ----
676 ----
677 // Make sure it's NOT the post increment register that we are going to ----
678 // new value. ----
679 if (HII->isPostIncrement(MI) && 0
680 getPostIncrementOperand(MI, HII).getReg() == DepReg) { 0
681 return false; 0
682 } ----
683 ----
684 if (HII->isPostIncrement(PacketMI) && PacketMI.mayLoad() && 0
685 getPostIncrementOperand(PacketMI, HII).getReg() == DepReg) { 0
686 // If source is post_inc, or absolute-set addressing, it can not feed ----
687 // into new value store ----
688 // r3 = memw(r2++#4) ----
689 // memw(r30 + #-1404) = r2.new -> can not be new value store ----
690 // arch spec section: 5.4.2.1. ----
691 return false; 0
692 } ----
693 ----
694 if (isLoadAbsSet(PacketMI) && getAbsSetOperand(PacketMI).getReg() == DepReg) 0
695 return false; 0
696 ----
697 // If the source that feeds the store is predicated, new value store must ----
698 // also be predicated. ----
699 if (HII->isPredicated(PacketMI)) { 0
700 if (!HII->isPredicated(MI)) 0
701 return false; 0
702 ----
703 // Check to make sure that they both will have their predicates ----
704 // evaluate identically. ----
705 unsigned predRegNumSrc = 0; 0
706 unsigned predRegNumDst = 0; 0
707 const TargetRegisterClass* predRegClass = nullptr; 0
708 ----
709 // Get predicate register used in the source instruction. ----
710 for (auto &MO : PacketMI.operands()) { 0
711 if (!MO.isReg()) 0
712 continue; 0
713 predRegNumSrc = MO.getReg(); 0
714 predRegClass = HRI->getMinimalPhysRegClass(predRegNumSrc); 0
715 if (predRegClass == &Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass) 0
716 break; 0
717 } ----
718 assert((predRegClass == &Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass) && 0
719 "predicate register not found in a predicated PacketMI instruction"); ----
720 ----
721 // Get predicate register used in new-value store instruction. ----
722 for (auto &MO : MI.operands()) { 0
723 if (!MO.isReg()) 0
724 continue; 0
725 predRegNumDst = MO.getReg(); 0
726 predRegClass = HRI->getMinimalPhysRegClass(predRegNumDst); 0
727 if (predRegClass == &Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass) 0
728 break; 0
729 } ----
730 assert((predRegClass == &Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass) && 0
731 "predicate register not found in a predicated MI instruction"); ----
732 ----
733 // New-value register producer and user (store) need to satisfy these ----
734 // constraints: ----
735 // 1) Both instructions should be predicated on the same register. ----
736 // 2) If producer of the new-value register is .new predicated then store ----
737 // should also be .new predicated and if producer is not .new predicated ----
738 // then store should not be .new predicated. ----
739 // 3) Both new-value register producer and user should have same predicate ----
740 // sense, i.e, either both should be negated or both should be non-negated. ----
741 if (predRegNumDst != predRegNumSrc || 0
742 HII->isDotNewInst(PacketMI) != HII->isDotNewInst(MI) || 0
743 getPredicateSense(MI, HII) != getPredicateSense(PacketMI, HII)) 0
744 return false; 0
745 } ----
746 ----
747 // Make sure that other than the new-value register no other store instruction ----
748 // register has been modified in the same packet. Predicate registers can be ----
749 // modified by they should not be modified between the producer and the store ----
750 // instruction as it will make them both conditional on different values. ----
751 // We already know this to be true for all the instructions before and ----
752 // including PacketMI. Howerver, we need to perform the check for the ----
753 // remaining instructions in the packet. ----
754 ----
755 unsigned StartCheck = 0; 0
756 ----
757 for (auto *I : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
758 SUnit *TempSU = MIToSUnit.find(I)->second; 0
759 MachineInstr &TempMI = *TempSU->getInstr(); 0
760 ----
761 // Following condition is true for all the instructions until PacketMI is ----
762 // reached (StartCheck is set to 0 before the for loop). ----
763 // StartCheck flag is 1 for all the instructions after PacketMI. ----
764 if (&TempMI != &PacketMI && !StartCheck) // Start processing only after 0
765 continue; // encountering PacketMI. 0
766 ----
767 StartCheck = 1; 0
768 if (&TempMI == &PacketMI) // We don't want to check PacketMI for dependence. 0
769 continue; 0
770 ----
771 for (auto &MO : MI.operands()) 0
772 if (MO.isReg() && TempSU->getInstr()->modifiesRegister(MO.getReg(), HRI)) 0
773 return false; 0
774 } ----
775 ----
776 // Make sure that for non-POST_INC stores: ----
777 // 1. The only use of reg is DepReg and no other registers. ----
778 // This handles base+index registers. ----
779 // The following store can not be dot new. ----
780 // Eg. r0 = add(r0, #3) ----
781 // memw(r1+r0<<#2) = r0 ----
782 if (!HII->isPostIncrement(MI)) { 0
783 for (unsigned opNum = 0; opNum < MI.getNumOperands()-1; opNum++) { 0
784 const MachineOperand &MO = MI.getOperand(opNum); 0
785 if (MO.isReg() && MO.getReg() == DepReg) 0
786 return false; 0
787 } ----
788 } ----
789 ----
790 // If data definition is because of implicit definition of the register, ----
791 // do not newify the store. Eg. ----
792 // %r9 = ZXTH %r12, implicit %d6, implicit-def %r12 ----
793 // S2_storerh_io %r8, 2, killed %r12; mem:ST2[%scevgep343] ----
794 for (auto &MO : PacketMI.operands()) { 0
795 if (MO.isRegMask() && MO.clobbersPhysReg(DepReg)) 0
796 return false; 0
797 if (!MO.isReg() || !MO.isDef() || !MO.isImplicit()) 0
798 continue; 0
799 Register R = MO.getReg(); 0
800 if (R == DepReg || HRI->isSuperRegister(DepReg, R)) 0
801 return false; 0
802 } ----
803 ----
804 // Handle imp-use of super reg case. There is a target independent side ----
805 // change that should prevent this situation but I am handling it for ----
806 // just-in-case. For example, we cannot newify R2 in the following case: ----
807 // %r3 = A2_tfrsi 0; ----
808 // S2_storeri_io killed %r0, 0, killed %r2, implicit killed %d1; ----
809 for (auto &MO : MI.operands()) { 0
810 if (MO.isReg() && MO.isUse() && MO.isImplicit() && MO.getReg() == DepReg) 0
811 return false; 0
812 } ----
813 ----
814 // Can be dot new store. ----
815 return true; 0
816 } ----
817 ----
818 // Can this MI to promoted to either new value store or new value jump. ----
819 bool HexagonPacketizerList::canPromoteToNewValue(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
820 const SUnit *PacketSU, unsigned DepReg, ----
821 MachineBasicBlock::iterator &MII) { ----
822 if (!HII->mayBeNewStore(MI)) 0
823 return false; 0
824 ----
825 // Check to see the store can be new value'ed. ----
826 MachineInstr &PacketMI = *PacketSU->getInstr(); 0
827 if (canPromoteToNewValueStore(MI, PacketMI, DepReg)) 0
828 return true; 0
829 ----
830 // Check to see the compare/jump can be new value'ed. ----
831 // This is done as a pass on its own. Don't need to check it here. ----
832 return false; 0
833 } ----
834 ----
835 static bool isImplicitDependency(const MachineInstr &I, bool CheckDef, 0
836 unsigned DepReg) { ----
837 for (auto &MO : I.operands()) { 0
838 if (CheckDef && MO.isRegMask() && MO.clobbersPhysReg(DepReg)) 0
839 return true; 0
840 if (!MO.isReg() || MO.getReg() != DepReg || !MO.isImplicit()) 0
841 continue; 0
842 if (CheckDef == MO.isDef()) 0
843 return true; 0
844 } ----
845 return false; 0
846 } ----
847 ----
848 // Check to see if an instruction can be dot new. ----
849 bool HexagonPacketizerList::canPromoteToDotNew(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
850 const SUnit *PacketSU, unsigned DepReg, MachineBasicBlock::iterator &MII, ----
851 const TargetRegisterClass* RC) { ----
852 // Already a dot new instruction. ----
853 if (HII->isDotNewInst(MI) && !HII->mayBeNewStore(MI)) 0
854 return false; 0
855 ----
856 if (!isNewifiable(MI, RC)) 0
857 return false; 0
858 ----
859 const MachineInstr &PI = *PacketSU->getInstr(); 0
860 ----
861 // The "new value" cannot come from inline asm. ----
862 if (PI.isInlineAsm()) 0
863 return false; 0
864 ----
865 // IMPLICIT_DEFs won't materialize as real instructions, so .new makes no ----
866 // sense. ----
867 if (PI.isImplicitDef()) 0
868 return false; 0
869 ----
870 // If dependency is trough an implicitly defined register, we should not ----
871 // newify the use. ----
872 if (isImplicitDependency(PI, true, DepReg) || 0
873 isImplicitDependency(MI, false, DepReg)) 0
874 return false; 0
875 ----
876 const MCInstrDesc& MCID = PI.getDesc(); 0
877 const TargetRegisterClass *VecRC = HII->getRegClass(MCID, 0, HRI, MF); 0
878 if (DisableVecDblNVStores && VecRC == &Hexagon::HvxWRRegClass) 0
879 return false; 0
880 ----
881 // predicate .new ----
882 if (RC == &Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass) 0
883 return HII->predCanBeUsedAsDotNew(PI, DepReg); 0
884 ----
885 if (RC != &Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass && !HII->mayBeNewStore(MI)) 0
886 return false; 0
887 ----
888 // Create a dot new machine instruction to see if resources can be ----
889 // allocated. If not, bail out now. ----
890 int NewOpcode = (RC != &Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass) ? HII->getDotNewOp(MI) : 0
891 HII->getDotNewPredOp(MI, MBPI); 0
892 const MCInstrDesc &D = HII->get(NewOpcode); 0
893 MachineInstr *NewMI = MF.CreateMachineInstr(D, DebugLoc()); 0
894 bool ResourcesAvailable = ResourceTracker->canReserveResources(*NewMI); 0
895 MF.deleteMachineInstr(NewMI); 0
896 if (!ResourcesAvailable) 0
897 return false; 0
898 ----
899 // New Value Store only. New Value Jump generated as a separate pass. ----
900 if (!canPromoteToNewValue(MI, PacketSU, DepReg, MII)) 0
901 return false; 0
902 ----
903 return true; 0
904 } ----
905 ----
906 // Go through the packet instructions and search for an anti dependency between ----
907 // them and DepReg from MI. Consider this case: ----
908 // Trying to add ----
909 // a) %r1 = TFRI_cdNotPt %p3, 2 ----
910 // to this packet: ----
911 // { ----
912 // b) %p0 = C2_or killed %p3, killed %p0 ----
913 // c) %p3 = C2_tfrrp %r23 ----
914 // d) %r1 = C2_cmovenewit %p3, 4 ----
915 // } ----
916 // The P3 from a) and d) will be complements after ----
917 // a)'s P3 is converted to .new form ----
918 // Anti-dep between c) and b) is irrelevant for this case ----
919 bool HexagonPacketizerList::restrictingDepExistInPacket(MachineInstr &MI, 0
920 unsigned DepReg) { ----
921 SUnit *PacketSUDep = MIToSUnit.find(&MI)->second; 0
922 ----
923 for (auto *I : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
924 // We only care for dependencies to predicated instructions ----
925 if (!HII->isPredicated(*I)) 0
926 continue; 0
927 ----
928 // Scheduling Unit for current insn in the packet ----
929 SUnit *PacketSU = MIToSUnit.find(I)->second; 0
930 ----
931 // Look at dependencies between current members of the packet and ----
932 // predicate defining instruction MI. Make sure that dependency is ----
933 // on the exact register we care about. ----
934 if (PacketSU->isSucc(PacketSUDep)) { 0
935 for (unsigned i = 0; i < PacketSU->Succs.size(); ++i) { 0
936 auto &Dep = PacketSU->Succs[i]; 0
937 if (Dep.getSUnit() == PacketSUDep && Dep.getKind() == SDep::Anti && 0
938 Dep.getReg() == DepReg) 0
939 return true; 0
940 } ----
941 } ----
942 } ----
943 ----
944 return false; 0
945 } ----
946 ----
947 /// Gets the predicate register of a predicated instruction. ----
948 static unsigned getPredicatedRegister(MachineInstr &MI, 0
949 const HexagonInstrInfo *QII) { ----
950 /// We use the following rule: The first predicate register that is a use is ----
951 /// the predicate register of a predicated instruction. ----
952 assert(QII->isPredicated(MI) && "Must be predicated instruction"); 0
953 ----
954 for (auto &Op : MI.operands()) { 0
955 if (Op.isReg() && Op.getReg() && Op.isUse() && 0
956 Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass.contains(Op.getReg())) 0
957 return Op.getReg(); 0
958 } ----
959 ----
960 llvm_unreachable("Unknown instruction operand layout"); 0
961 return 0; ----
962 } ----
963 ----
964 // Given two predicated instructions, this function detects whether ----
965 // the predicates are complements. ----
966 bool HexagonPacketizerList::arePredicatesComplements(MachineInstr &MI1, 0
967 MachineInstr &MI2) { ----
968 // If we don't know the predicate sense of the instructions bail out early, we ----
969 // need it later. ----
970 if (getPredicateSense(MI1, HII) == PK_Unknown || 0
971 getPredicateSense(MI2, HII) == PK_Unknown) 0
972 return false; 0
973 ----
974 // Scheduling unit for candidate. ----
975 SUnit *SU = MIToSUnit[&MI1]; 0
976 ----
977 // One corner case deals with the following scenario: ----
978 // Trying to add ----
979 // a) %r24 = A2_tfrt %p0, %r25 ----
980 // to this packet: ----
981 // { ----
982 // b) %r25 = A2_tfrf %p0, %r24 ----
983 // c) %p0 = C2_cmpeqi %r26, 1 ----
984 // } ----
985 // ----
986 // On general check a) and b) are complements, but presence of c) will ----
987 // convert a) to .new form, and then it is not a complement. ----
988 // We attempt to detect it by analyzing existing dependencies in the packet. ----
989 ----
990 // Analyze relationships between all existing members of the packet. ----
991 // Look for Anti dependecy on the same predicate reg as used in the ----
992 // candidate. ----
993 for (auto *I : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
994 // Scheduling Unit for current insn in the packet. ----
995 SUnit *PacketSU = MIToSUnit.find(I)->second; 0
996 ----
997 // If this instruction in the packet is succeeded by the candidate... ----
998 if (PacketSU->isSucc(SU)) { 0
999 for (unsigned i = 0; i < PacketSU->Succs.size(); ++i) { 0
1000 auto Dep = PacketSU->Succs[i]; 0
1001 // The corner case exist when there is true data dependency between ----
1002 // candidate and one of current packet members, this dep is on ----
1003 // predicate reg, and there already exist anti dep on the same pred in ----
1004 // the packet. ----
1005 if (Dep.getSUnit() == SU && Dep.getKind() == SDep::Data && 0
1006 Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass.contains(Dep.getReg())) { 0
1007 // Here I know that I is predicate setting instruction with true ----
1008 // data dep to candidate on the register we care about - c) in the ----
1009 // above example. Now I need to see if there is an anti dependency ----
1010 // from c) to any other instruction in the same packet on the pred ----
1011 // reg of interest. ----
1012 if (restrictingDepExistInPacket(*I, Dep.getReg())) 0
1013 return false; 0
1014 } ----
1015 } ----
1016 } ----
1017 } ----
1018 ----
1019 // If the above case does not apply, check regular complement condition. ----
1020 // Check that the predicate register is the same and that the predicate ----
1021 // sense is different We also need to differentiate .old vs. .new: !p0 ----
1022 // is not complementary to p0.new. ----
1023 unsigned PReg1 = getPredicatedRegister(MI1, HII); 0
1024 unsigned PReg2 = getPredicatedRegister(MI2, HII); 0
1025 return PReg1 == PReg2 && 0
1026 Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass.contains(PReg1) && 0
1027 Hexagon::PredRegsRegClass.contains(PReg2) && 0
1028 getPredicateSense(MI1, HII) != getPredicateSense(MI2, HII) && 0
1029 HII->isDotNewInst(MI1) == HII->isDotNewInst(MI2); 0
1030 } ----
1031 ----
1032 // Initialize packetizer flags. ----
1033 void HexagonPacketizerList::initPacketizerState() { 0
1034 Dependence = false; 0
1035 PromotedToDotNew = false; 0
1036 GlueToNewValueJump = false; 0
1037 GlueAllocframeStore = false; 0
1038 FoundSequentialDependence = false; 0
1039 ChangedOffset = INT64_MAX; 0
1040 } 0
1041 ----
1042 // Ignore bundling of pseudo instructions. ----
1043 bool HexagonPacketizerList::ignorePseudoInstruction(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
1044 const MachineBasicBlock *) { ----
1045 if (MI.isDebugInstr()) 0
1046 return true; 0
1047 ----
1048 if (MI.isCFIInstruction()) 0
1049 return false; 0
1050 ----
1051 // We must print out inline assembly. ----
1052 if (MI.isInlineAsm()) 0
1053 return false; 0
1054 ----
1055 if (MI.isImplicitDef()) 0
1056 return false; 0
1057 ----
1058 // We check if MI has any functional units mapped to it. If it doesn't, ----
1059 // we ignore the instruction. ----
1060 const MCInstrDesc& TID = MI.getDesc(); 0
1061 auto *IS = ResourceTracker->getInstrItins()->beginStage(TID.getSchedClass()); 0
1062 return !IS->getUnits(); 0
1063 } ----
1064 ----
1065 bool HexagonPacketizerList::isSoloInstruction(const MachineInstr &MI) { 0
1066 // Ensure any bundles created by gather packetize remain separate. ----
1067 if (MI.isBundle()) 0
1068 return true; 0
1069 ----
1070 if (MI.isEHLabel() || MI.isCFIInstruction()) 0
1071 return true; 0
1072 ----
1073 // Consider inline asm to not be a solo instruction by default. ----
1074 // Inline asm will be put in a packet temporarily, but then it will be ----
1075 // removed, and placed outside of the packet (before or after, depending ----
1076 // on dependencies). This is to reduce the impact of inline asm as a ----
1077 // "packet splitting" instruction. ----
1078 if (MI.isInlineAsm() && !ScheduleInlineAsm) 0
1079 return true; 0
1080 ----
1081 if (isSchedBarrier(MI)) 0
1082 return true; 0
1083 ----
1084 if (HII->isSolo(MI)) 0
1085 return true; 0
1086 ----
1087 if (MI.getOpcode() == Hexagon::PATCHABLE_FUNCTION_ENTER || 0
1088 MI.getOpcode() == Hexagon::PATCHABLE_FUNCTION_EXIT || 0
1089 MI.getOpcode() == Hexagon::PATCHABLE_TAIL_CALL) 0
1090 return true; 0
1091 ----
1092 if (MI.getOpcode() == Hexagon::A2_nop) 0
1093 return true; 0
1094 ----
1095 return false; 0
1096 } ----
1097 ----
1098 // Quick check if instructions MI and MJ cannot coexist in the same packet. ----
1099 // Limit the tests to be "one-way", e.g. "if MI->isBranch and MJ->isInlineAsm", ----
1100 // but not the symmetric case: "if MJ->isBranch and MI->isInlineAsm". ----
1101 // For full test call this function twice: ----
1102 // cannotCoexistAsymm(MI, MJ) || cannotCoexistAsymm(MJ, MI) ----
1103 // Doing the test only one way saves the amount of code in this function, ----
1104 // since every test would need to be repeated with the MI and MJ reversed. ----
1105 static bool cannotCoexistAsymm(const MachineInstr &MI, const MachineInstr &MJ, 0
1106 const HexagonInstrInfo &HII) { ----
1107 const MachineFunction *MF = MI.getParent()->getParent(); 0
1108 if (MF->getSubtarget().hasV60OpsOnly() && 0
1109 HII.isHVXMemWithAIndirect(MI, MJ)) 0
1110 return true; 0
1111 ----
1112 // Don't allow a store and an instruction that must be in slot0 and ----
1113 // doesn't allow a slot1 instruction. ----
1114 if (MI.mayStore() && HII.isRestrictNoSlot1Store(MJ) && HII.isPureSlot0(MJ)) 0
1115 return true; 0
1116 ----
1117 // An inline asm cannot be together with a branch, because we may not be ----
1118 // able to remove the asm out after packetizing (i.e. if the asm must be ----
1119 // moved past the bundle). Similarly, two asms cannot be together to avoid ----
1120 // complications when determining their relative order outside of a bundle. ----
1121 if (MI.isInlineAsm()) 0
1122 return MJ.isInlineAsm() || MJ.isBranch() || MJ.isBarrier() || 0
1123 MJ.isCall() || MJ.isTerminator(); 0
1124 ----
1125 // New-value stores cannot coexist with any other stores. ----
1126 if (HII.isNewValueStore(MI) && MJ.mayStore()) 0
1127 return true; 0
1128 ----
1129 switch (MI.getOpcode()) { 0
1130 case Hexagon::S2_storew_locked: 0
1131 case Hexagon::S4_stored_locked: ----
1132 case Hexagon::L2_loadw_locked: ----
1133 case Hexagon::L4_loadd_locked: ----
1134 case Hexagon::Y2_dccleana: ----
1135 case Hexagon::Y2_dccleaninva: ----
1136 case Hexagon::Y2_dcinva: ----
1137 case Hexagon::Y2_dczeroa: ----
1138 case Hexagon::Y4_l2fetch: ----
1139 case Hexagon::Y5_l2fetch: { ----
1140 // These instructions can only be grouped with ALU32 or non-floating-point ----
1141 // XTYPE instructions. Since there is no convenient way of identifying fp ----
1142 // XTYPE instructions, only allow grouping with ALU32 for now. ----
1143 unsigned TJ = HII.getType(MJ); 0
1144 if (TJ != HexagonII::TypeALU32_2op && 0
1145 TJ != HexagonII::TypeALU32_3op && 0
1146 TJ != HexagonII::TypeALU32_ADDI) ----
1147 return true; 0
1148 break; 0
1149 } ----
1150 default: 0
1151 break; 0
1152 } ----
1153 ----
1154 // "False" really means that the quick check failed to determine if ----
1155 // I and J cannot coexist. ----
1156 return false; 0
1157 } ----
1158 ----
1159 // Full, symmetric check. ----
1160 bool HexagonPacketizerList::cannotCoexist(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
1161 const MachineInstr &MJ) { ----
1162 return cannotCoexistAsymm(MI, MJ, *HII) || cannotCoexistAsymm(MJ, MI, *HII); 0
1163 } ----
1164 ----
1165 void HexagonPacketizerList::unpacketizeSoloInstrs(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
1166 for (auto &B : MF) { 0
1167 MachineBasicBlock::iterator BundleIt; 0
1168 for (MachineInstr &MI : llvm::make_early_inc_range(B.instrs())) { 0
1169 if (MI.isBundle()) 0
1170 BundleIt = MI.getIterator(); 0
1171 if (!MI.isInsideBundle()) 0
1172 continue; 0
1173 ----
1174 // Decide on where to insert the instruction that we are pulling out. ----
1175 // Debug instructions always go before the bundle, but the placement of ----
1176 // INLINE_ASM depends on potential dependencies. By default, try to ----
1177 // put it before the bundle, but if the asm writes to a register that ----
1178 // other instructions in the bundle read, then we need to place it ----
1179 // after the bundle (to preserve the bundle semantics). ----
1180 bool InsertBeforeBundle; ----
1181 if (MI.isInlineAsm()) 0
1182 InsertBeforeBundle = !hasWriteToReadDep(MI, *BundleIt, HRI); 0
1183 else if (MI.isDebugValue()) 0
1184 InsertBeforeBundle = true; 0
1185 else ----
1186 continue; 0
1187 ----
1188 BundleIt = moveInstrOut(MI, BundleIt, InsertBeforeBundle); 0
1189 } ----
1190 } ----
1191 } 0
1192 ----
1193 // Check if a given instruction is of class "system". ----
1194 static bool isSystemInstr(const MachineInstr &MI) { 0
1195 unsigned Opc = MI.getOpcode(); 0
1196 switch (Opc) { 0
1197 case Hexagon::Y2_barrier: 0
1198 case Hexagon::Y2_dcfetchbo: ----
1199 case Hexagon::Y4_l2fetch: ----
1200 case Hexagon::Y5_l2fetch: ----
1201 return true; 0
1202 } ----
1203 return false; 0
1204 } ----
1205 ----
1206 bool HexagonPacketizerList::hasDeadDependence(const MachineInstr &I, 0
1207 const MachineInstr &J) { ----
1208 // The dependence graph may not include edges between dead definitions, ----
1209 // so without extra checks, we could end up packetizing two instruction ----
1210 // defining the same (dead) register. ----
1211 if (I.isCall() || J.isCall()) 0
1212 return false; 0
1213 if (HII->isPredicated(I) || HII->isPredicated(J)) 0
1214 return false; 0
1215 ----
1216 BitVector DeadDefs(Hexagon::NUM_TARGET_REGS); 0
1217 for (auto &MO : I.operands()) { 0
1218 if (!MO.isReg() || !MO.isDef() || !MO.isDead()) 0
1219 continue; 0
1220 DeadDefs[MO.getReg()] = true; 0
1221 } ----
1222 ----
1223 for (auto &MO : J.operands()) { 0
1224 if (!MO.isReg() || !MO.isDef() || !MO.isDead()) 0
1225 continue; 0
1226 Register R = MO.getReg(); 0
1227 if (R != Hexagon::USR_OVF && DeadDefs[R]) 0
1228 return true; 0
1229 } ----
1230 return false; 0
1231 } 0
1232 ----
1233 bool HexagonPacketizerList::hasControlDependence(const MachineInstr &I, 0
1234 const MachineInstr &J) { ----
1235 // A save callee-save register function call can only be in a packet ----
1236 // with instructions that don't write to the callee-save registers. ----
1237 if ((HII->isSaveCalleeSavedRegsCall(I) && 0
1238 doesModifyCalleeSavedReg(J, HRI)) || 0
1239 (HII->isSaveCalleeSavedRegsCall(J) && 0
1240 doesModifyCalleeSavedReg(I, HRI))) 0
1241 return true; 0
1242 ----
1243 // Two control flow instructions cannot go in the same packet. ----
1244 if (isControlFlow(I) && isControlFlow(J)) 0
1245 return true; 0
1246 ----
1247 // \ref-manual (7.3.4) A loop setup packet in loopN or spNloop0 cannot ----
1248 // contain a speculative indirect jump, ----
1249 // a new-value compare jump or a dealloc_return. ----
1250 auto isBadForLoopN = [this] (const MachineInstr &MI) -> bool { 0
1251 if (MI.isCall() || HII->isDeallocRet(MI) || HII->isNewValueJump(MI)) 0
1252 return true; 0
1253 if (HII->isPredicated(MI) && HII->isPredicatedNew(MI) && HII->isJumpR(MI)) 0
1254 return true; 0
1255 return false; 0
1256 }; 0
1257 ----
1258 if (HII->isLoopN(I) && isBadForLoopN(J)) 0
1259 return true; 0
1260 if (HII->isLoopN(J) && isBadForLoopN(I)) 0
1261 return true; 0
1262 ----
1263 // dealloc_return cannot appear in the same packet as a conditional or ----
1264 // unconditional jump. ----
1265 return HII->isDeallocRet(I) && 0
1266 (J.isBranch() || J.isCall() || J.isBarrier()); 0
1267 } ----
1268 ----
1269 bool HexagonPacketizerList::hasRegMaskDependence(const MachineInstr &I, 0
1270 const MachineInstr &J) { ----
1271 // Adding I to a packet that has J. ----
1272 ----
1273 // Regmasks are not reflected in the scheduling dependency graph, so ----
1274 // we need to check them manually. This code assumes that regmasks only ----
1275 // occur on calls, and the problematic case is when we add an instruction ----
1276 // defining a register R to a packet that has a call that clobbers R via ----
1277 // a regmask. Those cannot be packetized together, because the call will ----
1278 // be executed last. That's also a reson why it is ok to add a call ----
1279 // clobbering R to a packet that defines R. ----
1280 ----
1281 // Look for regmasks in J. ----
1282 for (const MachineOperand &OpJ : J.operands()) { 0
1283 if (!OpJ.isRegMask()) 0
1284 continue; 0
1285 assert((J.isCall() || HII->isTailCall(J)) && "Regmask on a non-call"); 0
1286 for (const MachineOperand &OpI : I.operands()) { 0
1287 if (OpI.isReg()) { 0
1288 if (OpJ.clobbersPhysReg(OpI.getReg())) 0
1289 return true; 0
1290 } else if (OpI.isRegMask()) { 0
1291 // Both are regmasks. Assume that they intersect. ----
1292 return true; 0
1293 } ----
1294 } ----
1295 } ----
1296 return false; 0
1297 } ----
1298 ----
1299 bool HexagonPacketizerList::hasDualStoreDependence(const MachineInstr &I, 0
1300 const MachineInstr &J) { ----
1301 bool SysI = isSystemInstr(I), SysJ = isSystemInstr(J); 0
1302 bool StoreI = I.mayStore(), StoreJ = J.mayStore(); 0
1303 if ((SysI && StoreJ) || (SysJ && StoreI)) 0
1304 return true; 0
1305 ----
1306 if (StoreI && StoreJ) { 0
1307 if (HII->isNewValueInst(J) || HII->isMemOp(J) || HII->isMemOp(I)) 0
1308 return true; 0
1309 } else { ----
1310 // A memop cannot be in the same packet with another memop or a store. ----
1311 // Two stores can be together, but here I and J cannot both be stores. ----
1312 bool MopStI = HII->isMemOp(I) || StoreI; 0
1313 bool MopStJ = HII->isMemOp(J) || StoreJ; 0
1314 if (MopStI && MopStJ) 0
1315 return true; 0
1316 } ----
1317 ----
1318 return (StoreJ && HII->isDeallocRet(I)) || (StoreI && HII->isDeallocRet(J)); 0
1319 } ----
1320 ----
1321 // SUI is the current instruction that is outside of the current packet. ----
1322 // SUJ is the current instruction inside the current packet against which that ----
1323 // SUI will be packetized. ----
1324 bool HexagonPacketizerList::isLegalToPacketizeTogether(SUnit *SUI, SUnit *SUJ) { 0
1325 assert(SUI->getInstr() && SUJ->getInstr()); 0
1326 MachineInstr &I = *SUI->getInstr(); 0
1327 MachineInstr &J = *SUJ->getInstr(); 0
1328 ----
1329 // Clear IgnoreDepMIs when Packet starts. ----
1330 if (CurrentPacketMIs.size() == 1) 0
1331 IgnoreDepMIs.clear(); 0
1332 ----
1333 MachineBasicBlock::iterator II = I.getIterator(); 0
1334 ----
1335 // Solo instructions cannot go in the packet. ----
1336 assert(!isSoloInstruction(I) && "Unexpected solo instr!"); 0
1337 ----
1338 if (cannotCoexist(I, J)) 0
1339 return false; 0
1340 ----
1341 Dependence = hasDeadDependence(I, J) || hasControlDependence(I, J); 0
1342 if (Dependence) 0
1343 return false; 0
1344 ----
1345 // Regmasks are not accounted for in the scheduling graph, so we need ----
1346 // to explicitly check for dependencies caused by them. They should only ----
1347 // appear on calls, so it's not too pessimistic to reject all regmask ----
1348 // dependencies. ----
1349 Dependence = hasRegMaskDependence(I, J); 0
1350 if (Dependence) 0
1351 return false; 0
1352 ----
1353 // Dual-store does not allow second store, if the first store is not ----
1354 // in SLOT0. New value store, new value jump, dealloc_return and memop ----
1355 // always take SLOT0. Arch spec 3.4.4.2. ----
1356 Dependence = hasDualStoreDependence(I, J); 0
1357 if (Dependence) 0
1358 return false; 0
1359 ----
1360 // If an instruction feeds new value jump, glue it. ----
1361 MachineBasicBlock::iterator NextMII = I.getIterator(); 0
1362 ++NextMII; 0
1363 if (NextMII != I.getParent()->end() && HII->isNewValueJump(*NextMII)) { 0
1364 MachineInstr &NextMI = *NextMII; 0
1365 ----
1366 bool secondRegMatch = false; 0
1367 const MachineOperand &NOp0 = NextMI.getOperand(0); 0
1368 const MachineOperand &NOp1 = NextMI.getOperand(1); 0
1369 ----
1370 if (NOp1.isReg() && I.getOperand(0).getReg() == NOp1.getReg()) 0
1371 secondRegMatch = true; 0
1372 ----
1373 for (MachineInstr *PI : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
1374 // NVJ can not be part of the dual jump - Arch Spec: section 7.8. ----
1375 if (PI->isCall()) { 0
1376 Dependence = true; 0
1377 break; 0
1378 } ----
1379 // Validate: ----
1380 // 1. Packet does not have a store in it. ----
1381 // 2. If the first operand of the nvj is newified, and the second ----
1382 // operand is also a reg, it (second reg) is not defined in ----
1383 // the same packet. ----
1384 // 3. If the second operand of the nvj is newified, (which means ----
1385 // first operand is also a reg), first reg is not defined in ----
1386 // the same packet. ----
1387 if (PI->getOpcode() == Hexagon::S2_allocframe || PI->mayStore() || 0
1388 HII->isLoopN(*PI)) { 0
1389 Dependence = true; 0
1390 break; 0
1391 } ----
1392 // Check #2/#3. ----
1393 const MachineOperand &OpR = secondRegMatch ? NOp0 : NOp1; 0
1394 if (OpR.isReg() && PI->modifiesRegister(OpR.getReg(), HRI)) { 0
1395 Dependence = true; 0
1396 break; 0
1397 } ----
1398 } ----
1399 ----
1400 GlueToNewValueJump = true; 0
1401 if (Dependence) 0
1402 return false; 0
1403 } ----
1404 ----
1405 // There no dependency between a prolog instruction and its successor. ----
1406 if (!SUJ->isSucc(SUI)) 0
1407 return true; 0
1408 ----
1409 for (unsigned i = 0; i < SUJ->Succs.size(); ++i) { 0
1410 if (FoundSequentialDependence) 0
1411 break; 0
1412 ----
1413 if (SUJ->Succs[i].getSUnit() != SUI) 0
1414 continue; 0
1415 ----
1416 SDep::Kind DepType = SUJ->Succs[i].getKind(); 0
1417 // For direct calls: ----
1418 // Ignore register dependences for call instructions for packetization ----
1419 // purposes except for those due to r31 and predicate registers. ----
1420 // ----
1421 // For indirect calls: ----
1422 // Same as direct calls + check for true dependences to the register ----
1423 // used in the indirect call. ----
1424 // ----
1425 // We completely ignore Order dependences for call instructions. ----
1426 // ----
1427 // For returns: ----
1428 // Ignore register dependences for return instructions like jumpr, ----
1429 // dealloc return unless we have dependencies on the explicit uses ----
1430 // of the registers used by jumpr (like r31) or dealloc return ----
1431 // (like r29 or r30). ----
1432 unsigned DepReg = 0; 0
1433 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = nullptr; 0
1434 if (DepType == SDep::Data) { 0
1435 DepReg = SUJ->Succs[i].getReg(); 0
1436 RC = HRI->getMinimalPhysRegClass(DepReg); 0
1437 } ----
1438 ----
1439 if (I.isCall() || HII->isJumpR(I) || I.isReturn() || HII->isTailCall(I)) { 0
1440 if (!isRegDependence(DepType)) 0
1441 continue; 0
1442 if (!isCallDependent(I, DepType, SUJ->Succs[i].getReg())) 0
1443 continue; 0
1444 } ----
1445 ----
1446 if (DepType == SDep::Data) { 0
1447 if (canPromoteToDotCur(J, SUJ, DepReg, II, RC)) 0
1448 if (promoteToDotCur(J, DepType, II, RC)) 0
1449 continue; 0
1450 } ----
1451 ----
1452 // Data dpendence ok if we have load.cur. ----
1453 if (DepType == SDep::Data && HII->isDotCurInst(J)) { 0
1454 if (HII->isHVXVec(I)) 0
1455 continue; 0
1456 } ----
1457 ----
1458 // For instructions that can be promoted to dot-new, try to promote. ----
1459 if (DepType == SDep::Data) { 0
1460 if (canPromoteToDotNew(I, SUJ, DepReg, II, RC)) { 0
1461 if (promoteToDotNew(I, DepType, II, RC)) { 0
1462 PromotedToDotNew = true; 0
1463 if (cannotCoexist(I, J)) 0
1464 FoundSequentialDependence = true; 0
1465 continue; 0
1466 } ----
1467 } ----
1468 if (HII->isNewValueJump(I)) 0
1469 continue; 0
1470 } ----
1471 ----
1472 // For predicated instructions, if the predicates are complements then ----
1473 // there can be no dependence. ----
1474 if (HII->isPredicated(I) && HII->isPredicated(J) && 0
1475 arePredicatesComplements(I, J)) { 0
1476 // Not always safe to do this translation. ----
1477 // DAG Builder attempts to reduce dependence edges using transitive ----
1478 // nature of dependencies. Here is an example: ----
1479 // ----
1480 // r0 = tfr_pt ... (1) ----
1481 // r0 = tfr_pf ... (2) ----
1482 // r0 = tfr_pt ... (3) ----
1483 // ----
1484 // There will be an output dependence between (1)->(2) and (2)->(3). ----
1485 // However, there is no dependence edge between (1)->(3). This results ----
1486 // in all 3 instructions going in the same packet. We ignore dependce ----
1487 // only once to avoid this situation. ----
1488 auto Itr = find(IgnoreDepMIs, &J); 0
1489 if (Itr != IgnoreDepMIs.end()) { 0
1490 Dependence = true; 0
1491 return false; 0
1492 } ----
1493 IgnoreDepMIs.push_back(&I); 0
1494 continue; 0
1495 } 0
1496 ----
1497 // Ignore Order dependences between unconditional direct branches ----
1498 // and non-control-flow instructions. ----
1499 if (isDirectJump(I) && !J.isBranch() && !J.isCall() && 0
1500 DepType == SDep::Order) ----
1501 continue; 0
1502 ----
1503 // Ignore all dependences for jumps except for true and output ----
1504 // dependences. ----
1505 if (I.isConditionalBranch() && DepType != SDep::Data && 0
1506 DepType != SDep::Output) ----
1507 continue; 0
1508 ----
1509 if (DepType == SDep::Output) { 0
1510 FoundSequentialDependence = true; 0
1511 break; 0
1512 } ----
1513 ----
1514 // For Order dependences: ----
1515 // 1. Volatile loads/stores can be packetized together, unless other ----
1516 // rules prevent is. ----
1517 // 2. Store followed by a load is not allowed. ----
1518 // 3. Store followed by a store is valid. ----
1519 // 4. Load followed by any memory operation is allowed. ----
1520 if (DepType == SDep::Order) { 0
1521 if (!PacketizeVolatiles) { 0
1522 bool OrdRefs = I.hasOrderedMemoryRef() || J.hasOrderedMemoryRef(); 0
1523 if (OrdRefs) { 0
1524 FoundSequentialDependence = true; 0
1525 break; 0
1526 } ----
1527 } ----
1528 // J is first, I is second. ----
1529 bool LoadJ = J.mayLoad(), StoreJ = J.mayStore(); 0
1530 bool LoadI = I.mayLoad(), StoreI = I.mayStore(); 0
1531 bool NVStoreJ = HII->isNewValueStore(J); 0
1532 bool NVStoreI = HII->isNewValueStore(I); 0
1533 bool IsVecJ = HII->isHVXVec(J); 0
1534 bool IsVecI = HII->isHVXVec(I); 0
1535 ----
1536 // Don't reorder the loads if there is an order dependence. This would ----
1537 // occur if the first instruction must go in slot0. ----
1538 if (LoadJ && LoadI && HII->isPureSlot0(J)) { 0
1539 FoundSequentialDependence = true; 0
1540 break; 0
1541 } ----
1542 ----
1543 if (Slot1Store && MF.getSubtarget().hasV65Ops() && 0
1544 ((LoadJ && StoreI && !NVStoreI) || 0
1545 (StoreJ && LoadI && !NVStoreJ)) && 0
1546 (J.getOpcode() != Hexagon::S2_allocframe && 0
1547 I.getOpcode() != Hexagon::S2_allocframe) && 0
1548 (J.getOpcode() != Hexagon::L2_deallocframe && 0
1549 I.getOpcode() != Hexagon::L2_deallocframe) && 0
1550 (!HII->isMemOp(J) && !HII->isMemOp(I)) && (!IsVecJ && !IsVecI)) 0
1551 setmemShufDisabled(true); 0
1552 else ----
1553 if (StoreJ && LoadI && alias(J, I)) { 0
1554 FoundSequentialDependence = true; 0
1555 break; 0
1556 } ----
1557 ----
1558 if (!StoreJ) 0
1559 if (!LoadJ || (!LoadI && !StoreI)) { 0
1560 // If J is neither load nor store, assume a dependency. ----
1561 // If J is a load, but I is neither, also assume a dependency. ----
1562 FoundSequentialDependence = true; 0
1563 break; 0
1564 } ----
1565 // Store followed by store: not OK on V2. ----
1566 // Store followed by load: not OK on all. ----
1567 // Load followed by store: OK on all. ----
1568 // Load followed by load: OK on all. ----
1569 continue; 0
1570 } 0
1571 ----
1572 // Special case for ALLOCFRAME: even though there is dependency ----
1573 // between ALLOCFRAME and subsequent store, allow it to be packetized ----
1574 // in a same packet. This implies that the store is using the caller's ----
1575 // SP. Hence, offset needs to be updated accordingly. ----
1576 if (DepType == SDep::Data && J.getOpcode() == Hexagon::S2_allocframe) { 0
1577 unsigned Opc = I.getOpcode(); 0
1578 switch (Opc) { 0
1579 case Hexagon::S2_storerd_io: 0
1580 case Hexagon::S2_storeri_io: ----
1581 case Hexagon::S2_storerh_io: ----
1582 case Hexagon::S2_storerb_io: ----
1583 if (I.getOperand(0).getReg() == HRI->getStackRegister()) { 0
1584 // Since this store is to be glued with allocframe in the same ----
1585 // packet, it will use SP of the previous stack frame, i.e. ----
1586 // caller's SP. Therefore, we need to recalculate offset ----
1587 // according to this change. ----
1588 GlueAllocframeStore = useCallersSP(I); 0
1589 if (GlueAllocframeStore) 0
1590 continue; 0
1591 } ----
1592 break; 0
1593 default: 0
1594 break; 0
1595 } ----
1596 } ----
1597 ----
1598 // There are certain anti-dependencies that cannot be ignored. ----
1599 // Specifically: ----
1600 // J2_call ... implicit-def %r0 ; SUJ ----
1601 // R0 = ... ; SUI ----
1602 // Those cannot be packetized together, since the call will observe ----
1603 // the effect of the assignment to R0. ----
1604 if ((DepType == SDep::Anti || DepType == SDep::Output) && J.isCall()) { 0
1605 // Check if I defines any volatile register. We should also check ----
1606 // registers that the call may read, but these happen to be a ----
1607 // subset of the volatile register set. ----
1608 for (const MachineOperand &Op : I.operands()) { 0
1609 if (Op.isReg() && Op.isDef()) { 0
1610 Register R = Op.getReg(); 0
1611 if (!J.readsRegister(R, HRI) && !J.modifiesRegister(R, HRI)) 0
1612 continue; 0
1613 } else if (!Op.isRegMask()) { 0
1614 // If I has a regmask assume dependency. ----
1615 continue; 0
1616 } ----
1617 FoundSequentialDependence = true; 0
1618 break; 0
1619 } ----
1620 } ----
1621 ----
1622 // Skip over remaining anti-dependences. Two instructions that are ----
1623 // anti-dependent can share a packet, since in most such cases all ----
1624 // operands are read before any modifications take place. ----
1625 // The exceptions are branch and call instructions, since they are ----
1626 // executed after all other instructions have completed (at least ----
1627 // conceptually). ----
1628 if (DepType != SDep::Anti) { 0
1629 FoundSequentialDependence = true; 0
1630 break; 0
1631 } ----
1632 } ----
1633 ----
1634 if (FoundSequentialDependence) { 0
1635 Dependence = true; 0
1636 return false; 0
1637 } ----
1638 ----
1639 return true; 0
1640 } ----
1641 ----
1642 bool HexagonPacketizerList::isLegalToPruneDependencies(SUnit *SUI, SUnit *SUJ) { 0
1643 assert(SUI->getInstr() && SUJ->getInstr()); 0
1644 MachineInstr &I = *SUI->getInstr(); 0
1645 MachineInstr &J = *SUJ->getInstr(); 0
1646 ----
1647 bool Coexist = !cannotCoexist(I, J); 0
1648 ----
1649 if (Coexist && !Dependence) 0
1650 return true; 0
1651 ----
1652 // Check if the instruction was promoted to a dot-new. If so, demote it ----
1653 // back into a dot-old. ----
1654 if (PromotedToDotNew) 0
1655 demoteToDotOld(I); 0
1656 ----
1657 cleanUpDotCur(); 0
1658 // Check if the instruction (must be a store) was glued with an allocframe ----
1659 // instruction. If so, restore its offset to its original value, i.e. use ----
1660 // current SP instead of caller's SP. ----
1661 if (GlueAllocframeStore) { 0
1662 useCalleesSP(I); 0
1663 GlueAllocframeStore = false; 0
1664 } ----
1665 ----
1666 if (ChangedOffset != INT64_MAX) 0
1667 undoChangedOffset(I); 0
1668 ----
1669 if (GlueToNewValueJump) { 0
1670 // Putting I and J together would prevent the new-value jump from being ----
1671 // packetized with the producer. In that case I and J must be separated. ----
1672 GlueToNewValueJump = false; 0
1673 return false; 0
1674 } ----
1675 ----
1676 if (!Coexist) 0
1677 return false; 0
1678 ----
1679 if (ChangedOffset == INT64_MAX && updateOffset(SUI, SUJ)) { 0
1680 FoundSequentialDependence = false; 0
1681 Dependence = false; 0
1682 return true; 0
1683 } ----
1684 ----
1685 return false; 0
1686 } ----
1687 ----
1688 ----
1689 bool HexagonPacketizerList::foundLSInPacket() { 0
1690 bool FoundLoad = false; 0
1691 bool FoundStore = false; 0
1692 ----
1693 for (auto *MJ : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
1694 unsigned Opc = MJ->getOpcode(); 0
1695 if (Opc == Hexagon::S2_allocframe || Opc == Hexagon::L2_deallocframe) 0
1696 continue; 0
1697 if (HII->isMemOp(*MJ)) 0
1698 continue; 0
1699 if (MJ->mayLoad()) 0
1700 FoundLoad = true; 0
1701 if (MJ->mayStore() && !HII->isNewValueStore(*MJ)) 0
1702 FoundStore = true; 0
1703 } ----
1704 return FoundLoad && FoundStore; 0
1705 } ----
1706 ----
1707 ----
1708 MachineBasicBlock::iterator ----
1709 HexagonPacketizerList::addToPacket(MachineInstr &MI) { 0
1710 MachineBasicBlock::iterator MII = MI.getIterator(); 0
1711 MachineBasicBlock *MBB = MI.getParent(); 0
1712 ----
1713 if (CurrentPacketMIs.empty()) { 0
1714 PacketStalls = false; 0
1715 PacketStallCycles = 0; 0
1716 } ----
1717 PacketStalls |= producesStall(MI); 0
1718 PacketStallCycles = std::max(PacketStallCycles, calcStall(MI)); 0
1719 ----
1720 if (MI.isImplicitDef()) { 0
1721 // Add to the packet to allow subsequent instructions to be checked ----
1722 // properly. ----
1723 CurrentPacketMIs.push_back(&MI); 0
1724 return MII; 0
1725 } ----
1726 assert(ResourceTracker->canReserveResources(MI)); 0
1727 ----
1728 bool ExtMI = HII->isExtended(MI) || HII->isConstExtended(MI); 0
1729 bool Good = true; 0
1730 ----
1731 if (GlueToNewValueJump) { 0
1732 MachineInstr &NvjMI = *++MII; 0
1733 // We need to put both instructions in the same packet: MI and NvjMI. ----
1734 // Either of them can require a constant extender. Try to add both to ----
1735 // the current packet, and if that fails, end the packet and start a ----
1736 // new one. ----
1737 ResourceTracker->reserveResources(MI); 0
1738 if (ExtMI) 0
1739 Good = tryAllocateResourcesForConstExt(true); 0
1740 ----
1741 bool ExtNvjMI = HII->isExtended(NvjMI) || HII->isConstExtended(NvjMI); 0
1742 if (Good) { 0
1743 if (ResourceTracker->canReserveResources(NvjMI)) 0
1744 ResourceTracker->reserveResources(NvjMI); 0
1745 else ----
1746 Good = false; 0
1747 } ----
1748 if (Good && ExtNvjMI) 0
1749 Good = tryAllocateResourcesForConstExt(true); 0
1750 ----
1751 if (!Good) { 0
1752 endPacket(MBB, MI); 0
1753 assert(ResourceTracker->canReserveResources(MI)); 0
1754 ResourceTracker->reserveResources(MI); 0
1755 if (ExtMI) { 0
1756 assert(canReserveResourcesForConstExt()); 0
1757 tryAllocateResourcesForConstExt(true); 0
1758 } ----
1759 assert(ResourceTracker->canReserveResources(NvjMI)); 0
1760 ResourceTracker->reserveResources(NvjMI); 0
1761 if (ExtNvjMI) { 0
1762 assert(canReserveResourcesForConstExt()); 0
1763 reserveResourcesForConstExt(); 0
1764 } ----
1765 } ----
1766 CurrentPacketMIs.push_back(&MI); 0
1767 CurrentPacketMIs.push_back(&NvjMI); 0
1768 return MII; 0
1769 } ----
1770 ----
1771 ResourceTracker->reserveResources(MI); 0
1772 if (ExtMI && !tryAllocateResourcesForConstExt(true)) { 0
1773 endPacket(MBB, MI); 0
1774 if (PromotedToDotNew) 0
1775 demoteToDotOld(MI); 0
1776 if (GlueAllocframeStore) { 0
1777 useCalleesSP(MI); 0
1778 GlueAllocframeStore = false; 0
1779 } ----
1780 ResourceTracker->reserveResources(MI); 0
1781 reserveResourcesForConstExt(); 0
1782 } ----
1783 ----
1784 CurrentPacketMIs.push_back(&MI); 0
1785 return MII; 0
1786 } ----
1787 ----
1788 void HexagonPacketizerList::endPacket(MachineBasicBlock *MBB, 0
1789 MachineBasicBlock::iterator EndMI) { ----
1790 // Replace VLIWPacketizerList::endPacket(MBB, EndMI). ----
1791 LLVM_DEBUG({ 0
1792 if (!CurrentPacketMIs.empty()) { ----
1793 dbgs() << "Finalizing packet:\n"; ----
1794 unsigned Idx = 0; ----
1795 for (MachineInstr *MI : CurrentPacketMIs) { ----
1796 unsigned R = ResourceTracker->getUsedResources(Idx++); ----
1797 dbgs() << " * [res:0x" << utohexstr(R) << "] " << *MI; ----
1798 } ----
1799 } ----
1800 }); ----
1801 ----
1802 bool memShufDisabled = getmemShufDisabled(); 0
1803 if (memShufDisabled && !foundLSInPacket()) { 0
1804 setmemShufDisabled(false); 0
1805 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Not added to NoShufPacket\n"); 0
1806 } ----
1807 memShufDisabled = getmemShufDisabled(); 0
1808 ----
1809 OldPacketMIs.clear(); 0
1810 for (MachineInstr *MI : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
1811 MachineBasicBlock::instr_iterator NextMI = std::next(MI->getIterator()); 0
1812 for (auto &I : make_range(HII->expandVGatherPseudo(*MI), NextMI)) 0
1813 OldPacketMIs.push_back(&I); 0
1814 } ----
1815 CurrentPacketMIs.clear(); 0
1816 ----
1817 if (OldPacketMIs.size() > 1) { 0
1818 MachineBasicBlock::instr_iterator FirstMI(OldPacketMIs.front()); 0
1819 MachineBasicBlock::instr_iterator LastMI(EndMI.getInstrIterator()); 0
1820 finalizeBundle(*MBB, FirstMI, LastMI); 0
1821 auto BundleMII = std::prev(FirstMI); 0
1822 if (memShufDisabled) 0
1823 HII->setBundleNoShuf(BundleMII); 0
1824 ----
1825 setmemShufDisabled(false); 0
1826 } ----
1827 ----
1828 PacketHasDuplex = false; 0
1829 PacketHasSLOT0OnlyInsn = false; 0
1830 ResourceTracker->clearResources(); 0
1831 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "End packet\n"); 0
1832 } 0
1833 ----
1834 bool HexagonPacketizerList::shouldAddToPacket(const MachineInstr &MI) { 0
1835 if (Minimal) 0
1836 return false; 0
1837 ----
1838 if (producesStall(MI)) 0
1839 return false; 0
1840 ----
1841 // If TinyCore with Duplexes is enabled, check if this MI can form a Duplex ----
1842 // with any other instruction in the existing packet. ----
1843 auto &HST = MI.getParent()->getParent()->getSubtarget(); 0
1844 // Constraint 1: Only one duplex allowed per packet. ----
1845 // Constraint 2: Consider duplex checks only if there is atleast one ----
1846 // instruction in a packet. ----
1847 // Constraint 3: If one of the existing instructions in the packet has a ----
1848 // SLOT0 only instruction that can not be duplexed, do not attempt to form ----
1849 // duplexes. (TODO: This will invalidate the L4_return* instructions to form a ----
1850 // duplex) ----
1851 if (HST.isTinyCoreWithDuplex() && CurrentPacketMIs.size() > 0 && 0
1852 !PacketHasDuplex) { 0
1853 // Check for SLOT0 only non-duplexable instruction in packet. ----
1854 for (auto &MJ : CurrentPacketMIs) 0
1855 PacketHasSLOT0OnlyInsn |= HII->isPureSlot0(*MJ); 0
1856 // Get the Big Core Opcode (dup_*). ----
1857 int Opcode = HII->getDuplexOpcode(MI, false); 0
1858 if (Opcode >= 0) { 0
1859 // We now have an instruction that can be duplexed. ----
1860 for (auto &MJ : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
1861 if (HII->isDuplexPair(MI, *MJ) && !PacketHasSLOT0OnlyInsn) { 0
1862 PacketHasDuplex = true; 0
1863 return true; 0
1864 } ----
1865 } ----
1866 // If it can not be duplexed, check if there is a valid transition in DFA ----
1867 // with the original opcode. ----
1868 MachineInstr &MIRef = const_cast(MI); 0
1869 MIRef.setDesc(HII->get(Opcode)); 0
1870 return ResourceTracker->canReserveResources(MIRef); 0
1871 } ----
1872 } ----
1873 ----
1874 return true; 0
1875 } ----
1876 ----
1877 // V60 forward scheduling. ----
1878 unsigned int HexagonPacketizerList::calcStall(const MachineInstr &I) { 0
1879 // Check whether the previous packet is in a different loop. If this is the ----
1880 // case, there is little point in trying to avoid a stall because that would ----
1881 // favor the rare case (loop entry) over the common case (loop iteration). ----
1882 // ----
1883 // TODO: We should really be able to check all the incoming edges if this is ----
1884 // the first packet in a basic block, so we can avoid stalls from the loop ----
1885 // backedge. ----
1886 if (!OldPacketMIs.empty()) { 0
1887 auto *OldBB = OldPacketMIs.front()->getParent(); 0
1888 auto *ThisBB = I.getParent(); 0
1889 if (MLI->getLoopFor(OldBB) != MLI->getLoopFor(ThisBB)) 0
1890 return 0; 0
1891 } ----
1892 ----
1893 SUnit *SUI = MIToSUnit[const_cast(&I)]; 0
1894 if (!SUI) 0
1895 return 0; 0
1896 ----
1897 // If the latency is 0 and there is a data dependence between this ----
1898 // instruction and any instruction in the current packet, we disregard any ----
1899 // potential stalls due to the instructions in the previous packet. Most of ----
1900 // the instruction pairs that can go together in the same packet have 0 ----
1901 // latency between them. The exceptions are ----
1902 // 1. NewValueJumps as they're generated much later and the latencies can't ----
1903 // be changed at that point. ----
1904 // 2. .cur instructions, if its consumer has a 0 latency successor (such as ----
1905 // .new). In this case, the latency between .cur and the consumer stays ----
1906 // non-zero even though we can have both .cur and .new in the same packet. ----
1907 // Changing the latency to 0 is not an option as it causes software pipeliner ----
1908 // to not pipeline in some cases. ----
1909 ----
1910 // For Example: ----
1911 // { ----
1912 // I1: v6.cur = vmem(r0++#1) ----
1913 // I2: v7 = valign(v6,v4,r2) ----
1914 // I3: vmem(r5++#1) = v7.new ----
1915 // } ----
1916 // Here I2 and I3 has 0 cycle latency, but I1 and I2 has 2. ----
1917 ----
1918 for (auto *J : CurrentPacketMIs) { 0
1919 SUnit *SUJ = MIToSUnit[J]; 0
1920 for (auto &Pred : SUI->Preds) 0
1921 if (Pred.getSUnit() == SUJ) 0
1922 if ((Pred.getLatency() == 0 && Pred.isAssignedRegDep()) || 0
1923 HII->isNewValueJump(I) || HII->isToBeScheduledASAP(*J, I)) 0
1924 return 0; 0
1925 } ----
1926 ----
1927 // Check if the latency is greater than one between this instruction and any ----
1928 // instruction in the previous packet. ----
1929 for (auto *J : OldPacketMIs) { 0
1930 SUnit *SUJ = MIToSUnit[J]; 0
1931 for (auto &Pred : SUI->Preds) 0
1932 if (Pred.getSUnit() == SUJ && Pred.getLatency() > 1) 0
1933 return Pred.getLatency(); 0
1934 } ----
1935 ----
1936 return 0; 0
1937 } ----
1938 ----
1939 bool HexagonPacketizerList::producesStall(const MachineInstr &I) { 0
1940 unsigned int Latency = calcStall(I); 0
1941 if (Latency == 0) 0
1942 return false; 0
1943 // Ignore stall unless it stalls more than previous instruction in packet ----
1944 if (PacketStalls) 0
1945 return Latency > PacketStallCycles; 0
1946 return true; 0
1947 } ----
